[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Failure in vibe coding always circles back to one of two problems. Underspecified plans or bad development practices in general. And you know, there\'s this joke my dad told me when I was younger, which I will censor a bit'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here, but it illustrates the problem. There\'s two bulls standing on top of a hill overlooking a field of cows. One of these bulls is older and wise, and the'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other one is much younger and full of spunk. And the younger one says, "We should run down there and kiss one of them." And the older bull pauses'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for a moment and says, "No, we should walk down there and kiss all of them." &gt;&gt; Those are adult words. Children present. And I think the moral of that story was meant to be that patience and long-term'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'planning is more valuable than speed. So, instead of just jumping into your next project or feature, pause for a moment and think about the fact that what makes great engineers great is that'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they are very good at planning. And the skill that I\'m about to show you a demo of helps us do exactly that. So, the tool itself is called Context 7, which I\'ve covered before on this channel, but'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what we\'re specifically looking at is their relatively new skill wizard. So, Context 7 is basically a tool that keeps up-to-date documentation for any tool realistically that you could want to'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use, so that language models and AI coding tools have the most up-to-date version of whatever you\'re building with. So, if we were going to build something, for example, with a Drizzle ORM, we don\'t have to worry about Codex'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or Claude Code or whatever using some like out-of-date improper version of this library in order to build what it\'s trying to build. So, for example, in this demo we\'re going to move through'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We\'re going to build like an authentication system using Clerk. If you don\'t know what Clerk is, it\'s basically like a hosted authentication solution, and inside of Context 7, we can see that they last updated this documentation 6 days ago, and if we were'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to scroll down, we can see all of the patterns and best practices and ways that Clerk themselves think we should use their tool. So, the value of Context 7 here is pretty clear and obvious. But'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s not really what this video is about. Because what Context 7 actually created was a system so that we can take all of this documentation and actually turn it into a bulletproof skill. And'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the translation of that is that any technology that they have that you could possibly want to use, you can now use it like the people that made it wanted you to use it. Now, before we show off how'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this actually works, let\'s talk for a second about why creating skills for this type of stuff is actually problematic. To create effective skills, you have to actually be somewhat'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'knowledgeable of the thing that you\'re trying to build a skill for. And so, you can try to argue about meta prompting or researching your way to knowing that stuff, but at the end of the day, you'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t know what you don\'t know. So, you can assume that it created you something comprehensive, but you realistically have no clue if it\'s actually comprehensive or complete or not. And so, this manifests really in three'

[03:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'specific ways. Number one, if you wanted to build a skill for something like Clerk, which we\'re going to do in this video, you have to have a deep knowledge of the library itself. And really, what that means is you need up-to-date'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'current best practices for how all of this stuff actually connects and gets used in an app. Number two, you need to understand what are the do\'s and don\'ts that you need to be able to communicate to your coding tool like Claude Code.'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And number three, these things evolve over time, so you need to stay up-to-date with the actual library. And so, what happens is that most people don\'t actually use skills for the'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'libraries that they\'re using, and then you end up with all of these conflicting patterns inside of your project and things break. So, now that we know why Context 7 is really valuable and some of the pains of creating these skills'

[04:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ourselves, we can actually jump in and make one of these things. So, in order to run this thing, all you need is to copy this command that they have in this doc, which I\'ll link below the video, and then we can pop into a project and'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just paste in that command. And so, down here we\'re going to describe the expertise that we want it to have. So, in this case, we could say Clerk authentication. And now, what this is going to do is it looks through all of the sources that it has, again, from'

[04:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inside of its database of things. So, if I was to come through here, for example, and type in Clerk, it\'s pulling from this library of sources. So, if we pop back in here, we could say, "Hey, I want to use the first source," which in this'

[04:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'case is the official Clerk documentation. And now, what it\'s going to do is it\'s going to ask us follow-up questions. So, it wants to understand what exactly are we trying to do with Clerk in this case. So, I\'ll say that'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m using Next.js, which I am in this starter app that I\'ve spun up. What stage of development are we in? In this case, we\'re setting it up for the first time. And then, what aspect of the authentication do we want the skill'

[05:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'focused on? Because we don\'t want it to be a skill that talks about every single thing it could possibly refer to inside of the docs. If that were the case, we would just plug the docs in. And so, in this case, we\'re going to set up a'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sign-up sign-in flow, and so I\'ll say sign-up and sign-in flows. And so, what this is going to do is it goes out, it reads all of the sources [snorts] and the actual documentation inside of that library, and then it\'s going to use'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it to build us a skill that tells us how to do exactly what we said we wanted to do in part number three. So, now after it\'s gone through that, you can just install the skill directly. You can have'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it make changes. I\'m going to just install the skill, and it\'s going to install it into our project. So, if we were to pop in here now and look inside of our skills folder, we can see we have this Clerk Next.js authentication skill. And now, inside of it, we\'ve documented'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all of the critical rules that we need to follow in order to do this thing properly. And the thing that I really like about how this is structured is that it\'s telling us both the wrong way'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to do things and the right way to do things. And so, in this case with Clerk, it\'s talking about where this provider needs to go that wraps our entire application and tells it that it needs'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to use, you know, this authentication system. It\'s going to break down how the roots actually need to be structured properly, how the middleware needs to be integrated into our app in case we have like authenticated roots that certain'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'users can or can\'t access. It documents all the key patterns on how this thing should actually be used, what our environment variables need to look like, where they should go, how this gets integrated into what we have built, how'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the authentication pages should work, the entire thing that we need to get this really working. And then, the thing I really like, what are the common mistakes that we can force the language model to avoid. So, just to demo this thing, I have a really basic homepage, a'

[07:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sign-up page, and a dashboard, none of which is protected or has any configuration on it. Obviously, this dashboard is something we would only want a user to see once they were signed'

